  "text": "Node.js implements command injection prevention for the child_process module through a multi-layer security approach involving JavaScript input validation and C++ native bindings.\n\n**JavaScript Layer (lib/child_process.js):**\nThe module exports entry points: spawn(), exec(), execFile(), fork(), execSync(), execFileSync(), and spawnSync(). All async spawn functions ultimately call spawn() which uses normalizeSpawnArguments() to validate and normalize arguments. The normalizeSpawnArguments() function (line 538) performs null-byte validation on the 'file' parameter (line 540), 'args' array (line 556), 'shell' option (line 613), 'argv0' option (line 597), environment variables and keys (lines 691-692) via validateArgumentNullCheck(). The validateArgumentNullCheck() function (line 963) is a critical guard that checks if a string contains null bytes ('\\u0000') and throws ERR_INVALID_ARG_VALUE if detected, preventing null-byte injection attacks. The validateArgumentsNullCheck() function (line 970) extends this validation to array arguments.\n\n**Entry Points Chain:**\n- exec() (line 231) -> normalizeExecArgs() -> execFile() -> spawn()\n- execFile() (line 323) -> normalizeExecFileArgs() -> spawn()\n- fork() (line 122) -> validateArgumentNullCheck() on execPath -> spawn()\n- spawn() (line 745) -> normalizeSpawnArguments() with full validation\n- All validation occurs before creating the ChildProcess instance\n\n**JavaScript-to-C++ Bridge (lib/internal/child_process.js):**\nThe ChildProcess class (line 254) wraps a native C++ Process binding. Each instance contains this._handle = new Process() (line 266), which is the JavaScript representation of the ProcessWrap native object. The ChildProcess.prototype.spawn() method (line 354) calls this._handle.spawn(options) (line 395), passing the normalized and validated options to the C++ layer. This method also validates the options object and its envPairs array (line 378) before delegating to C++.\n\n**C++ Native Binding (src/process_wrap.cc):**\nThe ProcessWrap class (line 51) is a HandleWrap that exposes spawn() and kill() methods to JavaScript. ProcessWrap::Spawn() (line 153) receives the already-validated options from JavaScript. The C++ layer uses THROW_IF_INSUFFICIENT_PERMISSIONS (line 158-159) to check for child_process permissions. It extracts and processes spawn options: file (line 196), args array (lines 211-225), environment pairs (lines 239-251), stdio configuration (line 254), and various flags. Critical to security, the C++ code processes strings via node::Utf8Value which handles the already-validated strings from JavaScript (lines 196, 219-220, 245-246). The file, args, and environment are strdup'd and passed to uv_spawn() (line 286).\n\n**Permission Framework (src/permission/child_process_permission.cc):**\nThe ChildProcessPermission class enforces permission-based access control for child process spawning. The is_granted() method checks if child_process operations are permitted before spawn operations proceed.\n\n**Security Design:**\nThe null-byte validation in validateArgumentNullCheck() is the primary injection prevention mechanism. By validating at the JavaScript boundary before any native processing, Node.js prevents attackers from injecting null bytes to truncate commands in the argv and environment arrays. The validation covers: the executable file path, all command arguments, custom argv0 values, shell path, and all environment variable keys and values. This comprehensive approach ensures that malicious input cannot break out of argument boundaries or exploit null-byte termination in C strings passed to the operating system.\n\n**Files Involved:**\n- lib/child_process.js: Entry point functions and null-byte validation logic\n- lib/internal/child_process.js: ChildProcess class that wraps native binding\n- src/process_wrap.cc: Native C++ binding that interfaces with libuv and OS process creation\n- src/permission/child_process_permission.cc: Permission enforcement for child process operations\n- lib/internal/validators.js: General validation utilities"
}

